    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>People who are occupied or skilled in the handling of small watercraft such as canoes and rafts, typically on smaller bodies of water and waterways than oceans and very large lakes. For those who handle ships and other large watercraft, typically out to sea or on very large lakes, use "seamen."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000121095/Gayford, The Amateur Boatwomen (1996)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000121094/Merchants' Daughters: Women, Commerce... in South China (2010)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Gente que están ocupadas o habilitadas en el manejo de pequeñas embarcaciosnes tales como canoas y balsas, tipicamente en masas de agua y vías fluviales más pequeñas que oceanos y lagos de gran tamaño. Para aquellos que manejan barcos y otras embarcaciones grandes, tipicamente en alta mar o en lagos de gran tamaño, usar "marinero".</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>從事或專精於駕駛獨木舟和木筏等小型船隻者，一般僅航行於較小的水體和水路中，不會駛入海洋或大湖。至於在海洋或大湖上操縱駕駛船艦和其他大型水上交通工具者，則稱為「水手」一詞。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Mensen die zich bezighouden met of die zijn opgeleid in het besturen van kleine vaartuigen zoals kano’s en vlotten, doorgaans op kleinere waterwegen dan zeeën en grote meren. Gebruik ‘zeelieden’ voor hen die schepen en andere grote vaartuigen besturen, meestal op zee of op zeer grote meren.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Macehualmeh tlen motequihuihtoqueh zo tlamantli tlen motequihuia ipan cuecuetzitzin acalmeh tlen tlamamah, quence canoaz huan balzaz, motequihuiah ipan atlauhtli tlen tlahuel cuecuetzitzin huan axcanah ipan hueiatl. Para cequin tlen quitequihuiah huehhuei acalmeh huan cequinoc tlen tlahuel huehhuei, nemih ipan hueiatl zo pan acolli tlen tlahuel huehhuei, xictequihui "seamen."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Eastern Huasteca Nahuatl</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
